segments.text: We were just talking about you and Mr. Spence had divided the responsibilities in that he did the new construction and you did the renovation and maintenance.
And at what point was it that you separated departments then?
During the tenure of Dr. Morgan, Dr. Morgan had started trying to
get all of these college activities together and get them separated from the system, I guess.

There were a lot of them, and I was the only hanger-on, I believe, in the college down in the system administration building, and we just built this building for a physical plant over there, and although it wasn't intended at the time, I might have had to
taking a little stiffer hand in southern planning if they had, I moved over there and set up
And we were entirely separated.
So Mr. Spence then was with the system.
He was a manager of physical plant for the system.
His job was planning and construction for the entire system, including the university.
And you were then just for Texas A&M.
Right.
The operation and maintenance of the university.
So there is no college, in a sense, college architect or university architect anymore.
It's all a systems architect.
That's right.
Right now, Mr. Elkins is system architect.
And he does?
The system handles all, except minor projects, which the physical plant will handle.
Usually not new construction, but alterations and some smaller things.
I think they have authority up to $10,000, I believe.
That is the college buildings and utilities, or university buildings and utilities up to $10,000.
I've had a little bit of experience working with the architect's office in the renovation of the Cushing building where the archives will be moving later on.
The system architect's office did all of that.
The system physical plans office under Adam was the director of facilities planning and construction.
Let me back up a little bit.
and ask you a question pertaining to a later period.
I asked you the same question earlier.
That is about student laborers.
You mentioned that in the construction part, you didn't regularly, did not generally or could not generally use student laborers in construction.
This was in the pre-World War II days, which you had a lot of students in building maintenance, I mean, or janitorial.
work.
Did you continue that pretty much after the war when you came back?
No, it had been discontinued I guess during the war because
You see, at one stage during the war A&M had a relatively small student body.
Now they did have a number of military units here, what was it, student training that the government sent here and they were, I don't remember what it was, ASTP.
Some activity,
where the armed forces had great consistency.
They even had, I believe, most of the 12 dominoes occupied by the Navy.
And basically, full students were the rather low ebb at that time.
And if they hadn't had the Army and the Navy and the Air Force here going to school,
And they used, of course, many of the instructors for things that fitted in.
Once you take like the old, what was the old PMA building for years, down where the tennis courts in that area.
Now the Navy operated an electronics school there training
Naval personnel, electronics, and such.
You used the term PMA building, which stands for what?
Production Management.
It's a forerunner of AAA, and then whatever they call it now.
USDA?
No, USDA activity down there, giving people stuff for not planting stuff and all that.
OK.
It was a big, they had hundreds of employees down there in that thing, back in the early Roosevelt days.
After the war, one of the things I had some activity in was disposing of old buildings.
You know, we mentioned the Aggieland Inn.
I sold that to a firm in Austin and demolished it, hauled it off.
We had Austin, two of the early dormitories, Austin and Pfeiffer Halls.
They stuck around until post-World War II.
Yeah.
Old Austin Hall was one of the, I believe, not the only building that sat square with the world.

It faced the south, which in the early days of the college, the road came up the old main drive from the railroad station and post office and made a circle around and back, and it happened to be on the circle where it sat, north and south and east and west.
Also, there was Ross Hall, which we all have been for a long time, was the, originally a dormitory, sold that, and what was the name of the,
building over right across from the Koch building now, and that went over to Foster, Foster Hall, and sold that.
And then of course we had the job of getting rid of most of the houses on the campus then, starting with the group where the student center was built.
We had to clear that site in order to start construction there.
And they gradually disappeared to where we don't even have any over here on the Candy Hill.
It used to be called years ago.
Candy Hill?
How'd you get that name?
Lord, I don't know it was called that when I came here.
I don't know where it came from.
That would be in the area of what, say, across from here.
These last dormitories, up on this corner that's vacant, right up, well, you know they were.
When you came in, there was still a few employees' houses along the intersection of the Boulevard de Bryan, the extension of College Road.
Across the street, down from the engineering building.
Yeah, diagonally across from Zachary Hall.
Across what used to be the circles, now it's the squares.
Well, I believe somewhere over there is where Doc Asbury lived.
Yes.
Well, originally, he lived down here where the post office is, just back to the post office.
And he was quite a character.
And in fact, you have some of his Asbury Room in Cushing Library.
I don't know whether it's still called that or not.
But he donated his records and books on opera and painting reproductions and things.
But when the post office built, see, we gave that, I don't know, acre to the land, deeded it to the post office department of the US post office there.
And we had to move a railroad.
Well, the railroad had to be moved for construction of Walton Hall.

It went down in front of Walton Hall down the side of Speza because all the grocers were brought in on the train and went on down to the power plant to unload the coal, the lignite, and then on down back on what is now the petroleum building and what used to be Petroleum Geology, the one that had the tower on it.
Well, with the cattle pens, the stock came out.
Then that siding was moved and built Walton Hall.
And then it had to be rerouted again to make room for the four dormitories to come around and come up outside the post office, just north of the post office, and then back into those places.
Of course, in 1927 or 1928, we converted to gas and quit hauling in lignite.
shovel coal down there a few nights.
Is that while you were a student?
Yeah.
Shoveling off of the train car, or?
No, out of the bins into the boilers.
Of course, you had to travel the thing, but you had to shovel.
Doing a little bit of looking in our biographical file on you,
indicated that you had been on the College Station City Council from 46 to 53.
I served three terms on the City Council, soon after the war.
What years were they?
That would have been right after you returned, I think.
I think Tom Harrington was on that time, and I believe when he terminated and didn't run again, I believe that I
took his place on the council.
There was no problem serving on the city council?
No, except always that thing hung over us because we had two or three threats of suit for actions.
I remember one, there was a gentleman who raised chickens, which was against the
city ordinance, and he was directed to dispose of them, and he was threatened to sue us once to bring that up, but didn't.
Ernest Langford was mayor at the time, in fact for quite a long while, and one or two others, but they never did culminate in a suit.
Let's see, I guess now it would be possible to serve on the city council and also- Yes, I have a few that's on the city council.
Because of the recent- I would imagine those years when you were on the city council would have been one of a fair amount of growth of the city of College Station, would it not?
We had lots of problems of that sort because
I have a unique situation at College Station that was particularly more dominant in the early days because the community grew up around the periphery of the campus.
This tended to multiply or aggravate some of your problems because it wasn't a compact unit like Bryan grew out of a certain area in the beginning and expanded from that.
go around and of course there was very little commercial businesses of many sorts out here and particularly streets and utilities became a problem because they were strung out.
It's a different place now.
It's a different place than it was three years ago when I came.
My wife and I married at 19 and 30, that's a year after I completed my graduate work.
I was working at the University of New York College.
We couldn't get a place out of the counter station because there weren't very, very few.
Most of them were down here in what I told you is College Park.
And so we had to rent an apartment in Bryan.
That seemed like an awful long ways for me to go.
I'd try to go home for lunch, you know, and all.
At that point was the old Tuneville Trolley still in operation?
No, they had been discontinued and a taxi cab company had taken over.
I think it's the one that seemed like one of the operators of the, in urban, ran the original Taxi Service Twin College in Bryan.
But I know, I'd learned in my association with Ernest Langford that he was designing a couple of little matchbox duplexes.
Well, some, the professor and his wife were down in College Park.
My wife and I rented that apartment while he was
working on the plans in order to get one to get out of college.
It was not much bigger than your secretary's office in this room together, I guess.
Small bedroom, bathroom, kitchenette, and small living room.
I'd be rather happy to get it.
Even at that, though, it was a little bit more than the marriage students had when they came to Leavitt Park Hall.
There were very few Merritt students before the war.
Of course, they were growing more mostly in the graduate area.
But there were a few.
I remember one, Raymond Rogers, who was retired and lives down here south of campus.
When he came back the second time to go to A&M,
He rented what had been the maids' quarters, I believe, over Dr. Marsh's house.
You see, in those early days, most of the campus houses had a little outhouse back behind the house where the maids lived.
And later on, as it began to get a little more prosperous and the land students got greater and the maids didn't live in anymore,
They rendered them out to students.
